TY  - JOUR
T1  - Another look at the identification of current rational-expectations models
AU  - Rayner, Janne
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 47
IS  - 2
SP  - 305
EP  - 331
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/02/03/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(91)90105-M
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769190105M
AB  - This paper provides a complete treatment of the identification of the current rational-expectations model with generated forecasts of exogenous variables, as introduced by Pesaran (1981). It separates the question of the identifiability of the parameters of an RE model from that of the model's distinguishability from a non-RE model. It shows how some models, classified as ‘unidentified’, are identified. The paper offers a treatment of the surprise model and shows how, contrary to popular opinion, covariance restrictions are not needed to identify it. Conditions are developed that are easy to interpret and to check. It is shown how standard identification results for models without expectations can be applied to RE models that have been appropriately augmented.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Asymptotic optimality of generalized CL, cross-validation, and generalized cross-validation in regression with heteroskedastic errors
AU  - Andrews, Donald W.K.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 47
IS  - 2
SP  - 359
EP  - 377
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/02/03/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(91)90107-O
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769190107O
AB  - The problem considered here is that of using a data-driven procedure to select a good estimate from a class of linear estimates indexed by a discrete parameter. In contrast to other papers on this subject, we consider models with heteroskedastic errors. The results apply to model selection problems in linear regression and to nonparametric regression estimation via series estimators, nearest-neighbor estimators, and local regression estimators, among others. Generalized CL (GCL), cross-validation (CV), and generalized cross-validation (GCV) procedures are analyzed. The GCL and CV criteria are shown to be asymptotically optimal under general conditions. A feasible version of GCL, however, is available only in some applications. The GCV criterion is found to be asymptotically optimal only under a condition that is satisfied in some applications but not in others. For example, it is satisfied in the nearest-neighbor estimation context but not in the series estimation, local regression estimation, or model selection contexts. Thus, the CV criterion is the only feasible criterion of the three that is asymptotically optimal under general conditions. The proofs rely heavily on results of Li (1987).
ER  - 

